[7] Dengue antibody protects against Zika, Brazil
Date: Fri 8 Feb 2019
Source: Science 363 (6427): 607-610DOI: 10.1126/science.aav6618 [edited]
http://science.sciencemag.org/content/363/6427/607


Isabel Rodriguez-Barraquer, Federico Costa, Eduardo J. M. Nascimento, Nivison Nery Janior, Priscila M. S. Castanha, Gielson Almeida Sacramento, et al. Impact of preexisting dengue immunity on Zika virus emergence in a dengue endemic region.

Zika dynamics in South America
The infection dynamics of Zika virus (ZIKV) are difficult to characterize. Many ZIKV infections are asymptomatic, and the clinical presentation of ZIKV is nonspecific. Rodriguez-Barraquer et al. took advantage of a long-term health study under way in Salvador, Brazil, the epicenter of the recent outbreak in the Americas. They used multiple serological assays, from before and after the emergence of ZIKV in October 2015, to distinguish ZIKV immune responses from those against Dengue virus (DENV). About 73% of the population was attacked by ZIKV. The presence of preexisting antibodies to DENV was associated with less risk of ZIKV infection and fewer symptoms.

Abstract
The clinical outcomes associated with Zika virus (ZIKV) in the Americas have been well documented, but other aspects of the pandemic, such as attack rates and risk factors, are poorly understood. We prospectively followed a cohort of 1453 urban residents in Salvador, Brazil, and, using an assay that measured immunoglobulin G3 (IgG3) responses against ZIKV NS1 antigen, we estimated that 73% of individuals were infected during the 2015 outbreak. Attack rates were spatially heterogeneous, varying by a factor of 3 within a community spanning 0.17 square km. Preexisting high antibody titers to dengue virus were associated with reduced risk of ZIKV infection and symptoms. The landscape of ZIKV immunity that now exists may affect the risk for future transmission.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[These results in Salvador, Brazil, support similar findings of a study done in Nicaragua that also show that preexisting dengue antibodies in a pediatric cohort protect against Zika virus disease (see Zika virus (01): Americas, Asia research, observations 20190204.6293304). Because of the antigenic cross-reactivity between dengue and Zika viruses, it seems reasonable to assume that Zika virus infection with viremia is suppressed, but with enough antigenic stimulation by Zika virus to elicit an antibody response and clear the virus. The cross-reactive dengue antibodies may buy enough time for the Zika virus antibodies to clear the virus with little or no disease. Although earlier in vitro studies raised concern about the possibility of antibody-dependent enhancement (ADE) of Zika virus infections by preexisting dengue virus antibody in an ADE assay (see Zika virus (39): Americas, Europe 20160729.4378060), an in vivo rhesus monkey model did not confirm ADE (see Zika virus (15): Americas, research, observations 20170701.5144254). One hopes that ADE will not be of concern when Zika virus vaccines are applied in the field in the future. - Mod.TY]

******
[8] Zika in neotropical monkeys
Date: Thu 20 Dec 2018
Source: PLOS One https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0209391 [edited]
https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0209391


Krista M. Milich, Benjamin J. Koestler, Joe H. Simmons, Pramod N. Nehete, Anthony Di Fiore, Lawrence E. Williams, et al. Methods for detecting Zika virus in feces: A case study in captive squirrel monkeys (_Saimiri boliviensis boliviensis_).

Abstract
A strain of Zika virus (ZIKV) of Asian origin associated with birth defects and neurological disorders has emerged and spread through the Americas. ZIKV was 1st isolated in the blood of nonhuman primates in Africa and has been detected in the blood, saliva, and urine of a few catarrhine species in both Africa and Asia, suggesting that nonhuman primates may serve as both a source and a reservoir of the virus. The recent introduction of ZIKV to human populations in the Americas presents the potential for the virus to spread into nonhuman primate reservoirs. Thus, it is critical to develop efficient and noninvasive detection methods to monitor the spread of the virus in wild nonhuman primate populations. Here, we describe a method for ZIKV detection in noninvasively collected fecal samples of a Neotropical primate. Fecal samples were collected from two captive squirrel monkeys (_Saimiri boliviensis boliviensis_) that were experimentally infected with ZIKV (Strain Mexico_1_44) and an additional 2 uninfected squirrel monkeys. Nucleic acids were extracted from these samples, and RT-qPCR was used to assay for the presence of ZIKV using primers flanking a 101 bp region of the NS5 gene. In both ZIKV-inoculated animals, ZIKV was detected 5-11 days post-infection, but was not detected in the uninfected animals. We compare the fecal results to ZIKV detection in serum, saliva, and urine samples from the same individuals. Our results indicate that fecal detection is a cost-effective, noninvasive method for monitoring wild populations of Neotropical primates as possible ZIKV reservoirs.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This report raises the question of whether Zika virus can be maintained in wild non-human primate populations. If Zika virus has become established in wild primates, circulating in a sylvan (forest) cycle similar to that of yellow fever virus, that would make eradication of the virus impossible and assure that it would be, or has become, established in tropical countries in the Americas. There is some evidence that Zika virus infects wild non-human primates in Brazil. A 30 Oct 2018 published report indicates that Zika virus has been detected in 33 of 82 dead monkeys (free-living common marmosets, _Callithrix jacchus_, and black-striped capuchin, _Sapajus libidinosus_) found in Brazil near Sao Jose do Rio Preto, Sao Paulo State, and Belo Horizonte, Minas Gerais. Whole genome sequencing showed the virus to be very similar to the type that was infecting humans. Experimentally infected squirrel monkeys (_Saimiri_ spp.) and owl monkeys (_Aotus_ spp.) had viremia in the absence of detectible disease, and seroconversion occurred by day 28 (https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-018-34423-6). Detection of Zika virus infection by testing feces would provide a useful tool for surveillance of wild non-human primates in localities where Zika virus outbreaks in humans have occurred. - Mod.TY]
